  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Statement.}\nThe local topological dimension at the TZP may transition among nearby dimensional states:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\dim_p(M)\\in\\{n,n-1,n+1\\}.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $M$ be an $n$-dimensional manifold away from $p$. For $x\\neq p$,\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\dim_x(M)=n .\n\\end{equation}\n\nAt $p$, however, the metric degeneracy and lemniscatic self-intersection create a local ambiguity: two branches of the manifold meet at one point.\n\nA self-intersection may locally reduce distinguishable dimensional freedom, while bifurcation into two branches may locally increase effective adjacency. Therefore the local dimensional value is not fixed to $n$ alone, but may occupy the set:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\dim_p(M)\\in\\{n-1,n,n+1\\}.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nThe TZP acts as a dimensional seam. It is not merely located inside a dimension; it controls the transition between neighboring effective dimensional states.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
